{"title_page": "Success (Loretta Lynn song)", "text_new": "{{Infobox song\n| name       = Success\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Loretta Lynn]]\n| album      = [[Loretta Lynn Sings]]\n| B-side     = A Hundred Proof Heartache\n| released   = April 1962\n| format     = [[Gramophone record|7\" single]]\n| recorded   = September 1961<br />Bradley Recording Studio, [[Nashville, Tennessee]], [[United States|U.S.]]\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Honky-tonk|Honky tonk country]]\n| length     = {{Duration|m=2|s=36}}\n| label      = [[Decca Records|Decca]]\n| writer     = Johnny Mullins\n| producer   = [[Owen Bradley]]\n| prev_title = I Walked Away from the Wreck\n| prev_year  = 1961\n| next_title = World of Forgotten People\n| next_year  = 1962\n}}\n'''\"Success\"''' is a song written by Johnny Mullins that was originally recorded by American [[country music|country]] artist [[Loretta Lynn]]. It was released as a [[single (music)|single]] in April 1962 via [[Decca Records]]. \n\n== Background and reception ==\n\"Success\" was recorded at the Bradley Film and Recording Studio in September 1961. Located in [[Nashville, Tennessee]], the session was produced by renowned country music producer [[Owen Bradley]]. The song was recorded under her first session with Bradley and the recording label. Three other tracks were recorded on the same session.<ref>{{cite web|title=Praguefrank's Country Discography 2: Loretta Lynn, part 1|url=http://countrydiscoghraphy2.blogspot.com/2016/02/loretta-lynn-part-1.html|website=Praguefrank|accessdate=3 April 2016}}</ref> \n\nThe song reached number six on the ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' [[Hot Country Songs|Hot Country and Western Sides]] survey in 1962. The song ultimately became Lynn's first top ten hit and would start a series of further hits for Lynn under the label. \"Success\" was included on her debut studio album in 1963, ''[[Loretta Lynn Sings]]''.<ref name=\"Whitburn\">{{cite book |title= The Billboard Book Of Top 40 Country Hits: 1944-2006, Second edition|last=Whitburn |first=Joel |authorlink=Joel Whitburn |year=2004 |publisher=Record Research}}</ref>\n\n== Track listings ==\n;7\" vinyl single<ref>{{cite web|title=Success/A Hundred Proof Heartache by Loretta Lynn (Single, Country)|url=http://rateyourmusic.com/release/single/loretta_lynn/success___a_hundred_proof_heartache/|website=[[Rate Your Music]]|accessdate=3 April 2016}}</ref>\n* \"Success\" \u2013 2:36\n* \"A Hundred Proof Heartache\" \u2013 2:25\n\n== Charts ==\n=== Weekly charts ===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!align=\"left\"|Chart (1962)\n!align=\"center\"|Peak<br />position\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|US [[Hot Country Songs|Hot Country & Western Sides]] (''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'')<ref name=\"Whitburn\"/>\n|align=\"center\"|6\n|-\n|}\n\n== Sin\u00e9ad O'Connor version ==\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Success Has Made a Failure of Our Home\n| cover      = Sin\u00e9ad_O'Connor-Success_Has_Made_a_Failure_of_Our_Home.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Sin\u00e9ad O'Connor]]\n| album      = [[Am I Not Your Girl?]]\n| released   = 1992\n| format     =\n*[[7\" single]]\n*[[12\" single]]\n*[[CD single]]\n*[[cassette single]]\n| recorded   =\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = \n*[[Pop music|Pop]]\n*[[ballad]]\n| length     = 4:29\n| label      = \n*Ensign\n*Chrysalis\n| writer     = Johnny Mullins\n| producer   = \n*Phil Ramone\n*Sin\u00e9ad O'Connor\n| prev_title = [[The Emperor's New Clothes (song)|The Emperor's New Clothes]]\n| prev_year  = 1990\n| next_title = [[Don't Give Up (Peter Gabriel and Kate Bush song)#Willie Nelson and Sin\u00e9ad O'Connor version|Don't Give Up]]\n| next_year  = 1993\n| misc       = {{External music video|{{YouTube|4fQJgNW-lfE|\"Success Has Made a Failure of Our Home\"}}}}\n}}\n\nIrish singer [[Sin\u00e9ad O'Connor]] covered the song as \"'''Success Has Made a Failure of Our Home'''\" in 1992. It was released as the first and lead single from her third album, ''[[Am I Not Your Girl?]]''. {{Quote box|width=30%|align=left|quote=\"That's definitely the most biographical song on the album...the one that is the most personal. I didn't see it in terms of being a country song even though Loretta Lynn recorded it...but as a song that expressed something important...how everyone is concerned with material success and what that can do to people. Success has made a failure of our home...my home.\"|source=\u2014[[Sin\u00e9ad O'Connor]] talking about the song.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://books.google.no/books?id=vvwhAAAAIBAJ|title=Sinead O'Connor reinterprets the torch song|magazine=[[Reading Eagle]]|date=27 September 1992|accessdate=13 March 2020}}</ref>\n}} O'Connor first heard the song on a late '50s/early '60s album by American [[country music|country]] artist [[Loretta Lynn]].<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.americanradiohistory.com/UK/Music-and-Media/90s/1992/MM-1992-09-26.pdf|title=The Origins Of Sinead O'Connor's New Songcollection|magazine=[[Music & Media]]|date=26 September 1992|accessdate=20 February 2020|page=11|format=PDF}}</ref> The cover is produced by O'Connor with [[Phil Ramone]] and remains one of her biggest hits after it charted in several countries. The single peaked within the Top 20 in Ireland, Italy, the Netherlands and the United Kingdom, Top 30 in Belgium and Switzerland, and Top 40 in Australia and New Zealand. In the US, the single reached number 20 on the ''Billboard'' [[Alternative Songs]] chart.\n\nThe song was included on her compilation album, ''[[So Far... The Best Of]]'' in 1997.\n\n===Critical reception===\nThe song received favorable reviews from many music critics. [[Larry Flick]] from ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' commented, \"There's a new Sinead coming to town, as she previews her upcoming set of pop standards, ''\"[[Am I Not Your Girl?|Am I Not Your Girl ?]]\"'' Interestingly, she delivers one of the most assured, full-voiced performances to date, digging deep into the emotion of the material with a combination of heartfelt emotion and unbridled confidence. Will stun folks at first, though they will eventually become enthralled by the sincerity of this project.\"<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Billboard/90s/1992/Billboard-1992-09-05.pdf|title=Single Reviews|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=5 September 1992|accessdate=20 February 2020|page=76|format=PDF}}</ref> Greg Sandow from ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' called it a transformation of a [[Loretta Lynn]] song\" and wrote, \"Right at the start, a tortured brass riff tears it from its country roots. And at the end O\u2019Connor dissolves it into an all-but-deranged cry of despair, repeating \u201dAm I not your girl?\u201d for a full minute and a half, 27 times in all, with the brass shrieking behind her.\"<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://ew.com/article/1992/09/25/am-i-not-your-girl/|title=Am I Not Your Girl?|magazine=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|date=25 September 1992|accessdate=28 February 2020}}</ref> Tom Ewing from [[Freaky Trigger]] said that the song shows that O'Connor \"can belt with the best of them\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://freakytrigger.co.uk/ft/2010/10/sinead-oconnor-nothing-compares-2-u/#more-20020|title=SINEAD O\u2019CONNOR \u2013 \u201cNothing Compares 2 U\u201d|publisher=[[Freaky Trigger]]|date=29 October 2010|accessdate=7 March 2020}}</ref> ''Lennox Herald'' described it as a \"dramatic ballad with big band sound hit.\"<ref>\"SINGLES ROUND-UP\". ''Lennox Herald''. 4 September 1992. page 24. Retrieved 30 March 2020.</ref> ''[[Liverpool Echo]]'' wrote in their review, that the song \"could have been written for her\".<ref>\"Sinead O'Connor: Success Has Made A Failure Of Our Home\". ''[[Liverpool Echo]]''. 4 September 1992. page 41. Retrieved 30 March 2020.</ref> \n\n===Music video===\nA [[music video]] was made to accompany the song. In the video O'Connor performs the song on a press conference about child abuse while cameras are flashing. O'Connor imparts lyrics with [[sign language]].\n\n===Charts===\n====Weekly charts====\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n!Chart (1992)\n!Peak<br>position\n|-\n{{singlechart|Australia|37|artist=Sin\u00e9ad O'Connor|song=Success Has Made A Failure Of Our Home|rowheader=true|accessdate=20 February 2020}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Flanders|22|artist=Sin\u00e9ad O'Connor|song=Success Has Made A Failure Of Our Home|rowheader=true|accessdate=20 February 2020}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|Europe ([[Eurochart Hot 100]])<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.americanradiohistory.com/UK/Music-and-Media/90s/1992/MM-1992-09-26.pdf|title=Eurochart Hot 100|magazine=[[Music & Media]]|date=26 September 1992|accessdate=21 February 2020}}</ref>\n|35\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|Ireland ([[Irish Recorded Music Association|IRMA]])\n|11\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|Italy (''[[Musica e dischi]]'')\n|13\n|-\n{{singlechart|Dutch40|15|artist=Sin\u00e9ad O'Connor|song=Success Has Made A Failure Of Our Home|rowheader=true|accessdate=20 February 2020}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Dutch100|21|artist=Sin\u00e9ad O'Connor|song=Success Has Made A Failure Of Our Home|rowheader=true|accessdate=20 February 2020}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|New Zealand|32|artist=Sin\u00e9ad O'Connor|song=Success Has Made A Failure Of Our Home|rowheader=true|accessdate=20 February 2020}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Switzerland|28|artist=Sin\u00e9ad O'Connor|song=Success Has Made A Failure Of Our Home|rowheader=true|accessdate=20 February 2020}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|[[UK Singles Chart|UK Singles]] ([[Official Charts Company]])\n|18\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|US ''Billboard'' [[Alternative Songs]]\n|20\n|-\n|}\n\n== Cover versions ==\n\"Success\" has also been recorded by [[Elvis Costello]]. \n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Loretta Lynn singles}}\n[[Category:1962 songs]]\n[[Category:1962 singles]]\n[[Category:1992 singles]]\n[[Category:Decca Records singles]]\n[[Category:Loretta Lynn songs]]\n[[Category:Sin\u00e9ad O'Connor songs]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Owen Bradley]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Johnny Mullins (songwriter)]]\n\n{{1960s-country-song-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox song\n| name       = Success\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Loretta Lynn]]\n| album      = [[Loretta Lynn Sings]]\n| B-side     = A Hundred Proof Heartache\n| released   = April 1962\n| format     = [[Gramophone record|7\" single]]\n| recorded   = September 1961<br />Bradley Recording Studio, [[Nashville, Tennessee]], [[United States|U.S.]]\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Honky-tonk|Honky tonk country]]\n| length     = {{Duration|m=2|s=36}}\n| label      = [[Decca Records|Decca]]\n| writer     = Johnny Mullins\n| producer   = [[Owen Bradley]]\n| prev_title = I Walked Away from the Wreck\n| prev_year  = 1961\n| next_title = World of Forgotten People\n| next_year  = 1962\n}}\n'''\"Success\"''' is a song written by Johnny Mullins that was originally recorded by American [[country music|country]] artist [[Loretta Lynn]]. It was released as a [[single (music)|single]] in April 1962 via [[Decca Records]]. \n\n== Background and reception ==\n\"Success\" was recorded at the Bradley Film and Recording Studio in September 1961. Located in [[Nashville, Tennessee]], the session was produced by renowned country music producer [[Owen Bradley]]. The song was recorded under her first session with Bradley and the recording label. Three other tracks were recorded on the same session.<ref>{{cite web|title=Praguefrank's Country Discography 2: Loretta Lynn, part 1|url=http://countrydiscoghraphy2.blogspot.com/2016/02/loretta-lynn-part-1.html|website=Praguefrank|accessdate=3 April 2016}}</ref> \n\nThe song reached number six on the ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' [[Hot Country Songs|Hot Country and Western Sides]] survey in 1962. The song ultimately became Lynn's first top ten hit and would start a series of further hits for Lynn under the label. \"Success\" was included on her debut studio album in 1963, ''[[Loretta Lynn Sings]]''.<ref name=\"Whitburn\">{{cite book |title= The Billboard Book Of Top 40 Country Hits: 1944-2006, Second edition|last=Whitburn |first=Joel |authorlink=Joel Whitburn |year=2004 |publisher=Record Research}}</ref>\n\n== Track listings ==\n;7\" vinyl single<ref>{{cite web|title=Success/A Hundred Proof Heartache by Loretta Lynn (Single, Country)|url=http://rateyourmusic.com/release/single/loretta_lynn/success___a_hundred_proof_heartache/|website=[[Rate Your Music]]|accessdate=3 April 2016}}</ref>\n* \"Success\" \u2013 2:36\n* \"A Hundred Proof Heartache\" \u2013 2:25\n\n== Charts ==\n=== Weekly charts ===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!align=\"left\"|Chart (1962)\n!align=\"center\"|Peak<br />position\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|US [[Hot Country Songs|Hot Country & Western Sides]] (''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'')<ref name=\"Whitburn\"/>\n|align=\"center\"|6\n|-\n|}\n\n== Sin\u00e9ad O'Connor version ==\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Success Has Made a Failure of Our Home\n| cover      = Sin\u00e9ad_O'Connor-Success_Has_Made_a_Failure_of_Our_Home.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Sin\u00e9ad O'Connor]]\n| album      = [[Am I Not Your Girl?]]\n| released   = 1992\n| format     =\n*[[7\" single]]\n*[[12\" single]]\n*[[CD single]]\n*[[cassette single]]\n| recorded   =\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = \n*[[Pop music|Pop]]\n*[[ballad]]\n| length     = 4:29\n| label      = \n*Ensign\n*Chrysalis\n| writer     = Johnny Mullins\n| producer   = \n*Phil Ramone\n*Sin\u00e9ad O'Connor\n| prev_title = [[The Emperor's New Clothes (song)|The Emperor's New Clothes]]\n| prev_year  = 1990\n| next_title = [[Don't Give Up (Peter Gabriel and Kate Bush song)#Willie Nelson and Sin\u00e9ad O'Connor version|Don't Give Up]]\n| next_year  = 1993\n| misc       = {{External music video|{{YouTube|4fQJgNW-lfE|\"Success Has Made a Failure of Our Home\"}}}}\n}}\n\nIrish singer [[Sin\u00e9ad O'Connor]] covered the song as \"'''Success Has Made a Failure of Our Home'''\" in 1992. It was released as the first and lead single from her third album, ''[[Am I Not Your Girl?]]''. {{Quote box|width=30%|align=left|quote=\"That's definitely the most biographical song on the album...the one that is the most personal. I didn't see it in terms of being a country song even though Loretta Lynn recorded it...but as a song that expressed something important...how everyone is concerned with material succes and what that can do to people. Success has made a failure of our home...my home.\"|source=\u2014[[Sin\u00e9ad O'Connor]] talking about the song.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://books.google.no/books?id=vvwhAAAAIBAJ|title=Sinead O'Connor reinterprets the torch song|magazine=[[Reading Eagle]]|date=27 September 1992|accessdate=13 March 2020}}</ref>\n}} O'Connor first heard the song on a late '50s/early '60s album by American [[country music|country]] artist [[Loretta Lynn]].<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.americanradiohistory.com/UK/Music-and-Media/90s/1992/MM-1992-09-26.pdf|title=The Origins Of Sinead O'Connor's New Songcollection|magazine=[[Music & Media]]|date=26 September 1992|accessdate=20 February 2020|page=11|format=PDF}}</ref> The cover is produced by O'Connor with [[Phil Ramone]] and remains one of her biggest hits after it charted in several countries. The single peaked within the Top 20 in Ireland, Italy, the Netherlands and the United Kingdom, Top 30 in Belgium and Switzerland, and Top 40 in Australia and New Zealand. In the US, the single reached number 20 on the ''Billboard'' [[Alternative Songs]] chart.\n\nThe song was included on her compilation album, ''[[So Far... The Best Of]]'' in 1997.\n\n===Critical reception===\nThe song received favorable reviews from many music critics. [[Larry Flick]] from ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' commented, \"There's a new Sinead coming to town, as she previews her upcoming set of pop standards, ''\"[[Am I Not Your Girl?|Am I Not Your Girl ?]]\"'' Interestingly, she delivers one of the most assured, full-voiced performances to date, digging deep into the emotion of the material with a combination of heartfelt emotion and unbridled confidence. Will stun folks at first, though they will eventually become enthralled by the sincerity of this project.\"<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Billboard/90s/1992/Billboard-1992-09-05.pdf|title=Single Reviews|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=5 September 1992|accessdate=20 February 2020|page=76|format=PDF}}</ref> Greg Sandow from ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' called it a transformation of a [[Loretta Lynn]] song\" and wrote, \"Right at the start, a tortured brass riff tears it from its country roots. And at the end O\u2019Connor dissolves it into an all-but-deranged cry of despair, repeating \u201dAm I not your girl?\u201d for a full minute and a half, 27 times in all, with the brass shrieking behind her.\"<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://ew.com/article/1992/09/25/am-i-not-your-girl/|title=Am I Not Your Girl?|magazine=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|date=25 September 1992|accessdate=28 February 2020}}</ref> Tom Ewing from [[Freaky Trigger]] said that the song shows that O'Connor \"can belt with the best of them\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://freakytrigger.co.uk/ft/2010/10/sinead-oconnor-nothing-compares-2-u/#more-20020|title=SINEAD O\u2019CONNOR \u2013 \u201cNothing Compares 2 U\u201d|publisher=[[Freaky Trigger]]|date=29 October 2010|accessdate=7 March 2020}}</ref> ''Lennox Herald'' described it as a \"dramatic ballad with big band sound hit.\"<ref>\"SINGLES ROUND-UP\". ''Lennox Herald''. 4 September 1992. page 24. Retrieved 30 March 2020.</ref> ''[[Liverpool Echo]]'' wrote in their review, that the song \"could have been written for her\".<ref>\"Sinead O'Connor: Success Has Made A Failure Of Our Home\". ''[[Liverpool Echo]]''. 4 September 1992. page 41. Retrieved 30 March 2020.</ref> \n\n===Music video===\nA [[music video]] was made to accompany the song. In the video O'Connor performs the song on a press conference about child abuse while cameras are flashing. O'Connor imparts lyrics with [[sign language]].\n\n===Charts===\n====Weekly charts====\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n!Chart (1992)\n!Peak<br>position\n|-\n{{singlechart|Australia|37|artist=Sin\u00e9ad O'Connor|song=Success Has Made A Failure Of Our Home|rowheader=true|accessdate=20 February 2020}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Flanders|22|artist=Sin\u00e9ad O'Connor|song=Success Has Made A Failure Of Our Home|rowheader=true|accessdate=20 February 2020}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|Europe ([[Eurochart Hot 100]])<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.americanradiohistory.com/UK/Music-and-Media/90s/1992/MM-1992-09-26.pdf|title=Eurochart Hot 100|magazine=[[Music & Media]]|date=26 September 1992|accessdate=21 February 2020}}</ref>\n|35\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|Ireland ([[Irish Recorded Music Association|IRMA]])\n|11\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|Italy (''[[Musica e dischi]]'')\n|13\n|-\n{{singlechart|Dutch40|15|artist=Sin\u00e9ad O'Connor|song=Success Has Made A Failure Of Our Home|rowheader=true|accessdate=20 February 2020}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Dutch100|21|artist=Sin\u00e9ad O'Connor|song=Success Has Made A Failure Of Our Home|rowheader=true|accessdate=20 February 2020}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|New Zealand|32|artist=Sin\u00e9ad O'Connor|song=Success Has Made A Failure Of Our Home|rowheader=true|accessdate=20 February 2020}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Switzerland|28|artist=Sin\u00e9ad O'Connor|song=Success Has Made A Failure Of Our Home|rowheader=true|accessdate=20 February 2020}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|[[UK Singles Chart|UK Singles]] ([[Official Charts Company]])\n|18\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|US ''Billboard'' [[Alternative Songs]]\n|20\n|-\n|}\n\n== Cover versions ==\n\"Success\" has also been recorded by [[Elvis Costello]]. \n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Loretta Lynn singles}}\n[[Category:1962 songs]]\n[[Category:1962 singles]]\n[[Category:1992 singles]]\n[[Category:Decca Records singles]]\n[[Category:Loretta Lynn songs]]\n[[Category:Sin\u00e9ad O'Connor songs]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Owen Bradley]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Johnny Mullins (songwriter)]]\n\n{{1960s-country-song-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Mahagaja", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSin\u00e9ad O'Connor version:typo", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Success_(Loretta_Lynn_song)"}
{"title_page": "Vinny Arkins", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=July 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name               = Vinny Arkins\n| fullname            = Vincent Thomas Arkins<ref>{{Hugman|470|accessdate=25 March 2017}}</ref>\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1970|9|18|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Dublin]], Ireland\n| height              = \n| position            = [[Striker (association football)|Striker]] \n| youthyears1 =     \u20131986 | youthclubs1 = [[Stella Maris F.C.|Stella Maris]]\n| youthyears2 = 1986\u20131987 | youthclubs2 = [[Home Farm F.C.|Home Farm]]\n| years1              = 1987\u20131989 |clubs1 = [[Dundee United F.C.|Dundee United]] |caps1 = 0 |goals1 = 0\n| years2              = 1989\u20131991 |clubs2 = [[Shamrock Rovers F.C.|Shamrock Rovers]] |caps2 = 67 |goals2 = 28\n| years3              = 1991\u20131993 |clubs3 = [[St Johnstone F.C.|St Johnstone]] |caps3 = 48 |goals3 = 11\n| years4              = 1993\u20131995 |clubs4 = [[Shelbourne F.C.|Shelbourne]] |caps4 = 54 |goals4 = 21\n| years5              = 1995\u20131997 |clubs5 = [[Notts County F.C.|Notts County]] |caps5 = 38 |goals5 = 8\n| years6              = 1997\u20132006 |clubs6 = [[Portadown F.C.|Portadown]] |caps6 = 279 |goals6 = 179\n| years7              = 2006 |clubs7 = [[Bohemian F.C.|Bohemians]] |caps7 = 16 |goals7 = 2\n| years8              = 2007 |clubs8 = [[St Patrick's Athletic F.C.|St Patrick's Athletic]] |caps8 = 0 |goals8 = 0\n| totalcaps      = 502\n| totalgoals     = 249\n|nationalyears1 = 1986\n|nationalteam1 = [[Republic of Ireland national under-17 football team|Republic of Ireland U17]]\n|nationalcaps1 = 1\n|nationalgoals1 = 0\n|nationalyears2      = 1991\u20131995\n|nationalteam2 =   [[League of Ireland XI]]\n|nationalcaps2 = 3\n|nationalgoals2 = 0\n|nationalyears3      = 1990\u20131992\n|nationalteam3 = [[Republic of Ireland national under-21 football team|Republic of Ireland U21]]\n|nationalcaps3 = 8\n|nationalgoals3 = 1\n|nationalyears4      = 1992\n|nationalteam4 = [[Republic of Ireland B national football team|Republic of Ireland B]]\n|nationalcaps4 = 1\n|nationalgoals4 = 0\n|nationalyears5      = 2000\n|nationalteam5 =   [[Irish League representative team|Irish League XI]]\n|nationalcaps5 = 1\n|nationalgoals5 = 1\n|manageryears1 = 2010\u20132013\n|managerclubs1= Balydoyle United\n|manageryears2= 2013\u2013\n|managerclubs2= Malahide United (First Team Coach)\n|managerclubs3=[[Portadown F.C.|Portadown]] (Interim Manager)\n|manageryears3= 2016\n}}\n'''Vincent Thomas Arkins''' (born 18 September 1970) is an Irish retired [[association football|footballer]]. After retiring, he moved into management with Baldoyle United of the [[Athletic Union League (Dublin)|Athletic Union League]]<ref>http://www.baldoyleunited.com/2010/08/26/{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> and in 2016,he combined the two roles and came to help Ports Interim manager [[Pat McGibbon]] along with his current job at Malihide United Fc, as coach for the under 21 football club.\n\n==Club career==\nArkins scored 15 goals as Dundee United's youth team made it to the [[Scottish Youth Cup]] Final in 1989. After signing for [[Noel King]] for \u00a312,000 he made his [[League of Ireland]] debut for [[Shamrock Rovers]] against Bohemians on 15 October 1989 in a 3\u20131 win. Arkins went on to score 35 goals in 86 total appearances for The Hoops.\n\nHe won the Player of the Year award in his first season as well as sharing the [[PFAI]] Young Player of the Year award<ref>[http://www.rsssf.com/miscellaneous/ierpoy.html Ireland \u2013 Player of the Year and Other Awards] Rec Sport Soccer Statistics Foundation</ref> and was top club goalscorer that season and in 1990\u201391. He was also the first player to score at Rovers rented ground, the [[RDS Arena]], on 14 October 1990.\n\nDespite agreeing personal terms with [[Liam Brady]] to join [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]] in November 1991 the deal fell through as it was conditional on Celtic offloading some of their seven strikers. This deal would have been worth \u00a380,000 to Rovers with the bonus of home and away friendlies between the clubs.\n\nIn his last game for Rovers he scored against Galway at the [[RDS Arena]]<ref>{{cite news|title=Article| url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/archive/1991/1125/Pg016.html#Ar01602:05942807D43B32A54D3525620874280B043B0F659B11F5AE0C95A80F25BB1085EB1315FE0576BC0806CF19D40D1BA41935954D387562 | work=The Irish Times}}{{Dead link|date=June 2015}}</ref>\n\nArkins joined [[St Johnstone F.C.|St Johnstone]] for a reputed transfer fee of \u00a340,000 with additional bonuses based on appearances in November 1991<ref>{{cite news|title=Article| url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/archive/1991/1127/Pg017.html#Ar01700: | work=The Irish Times}}{{Dead link|date=June 2015}}</ref> Under the terms of the transfer fee to Rovers in 1989 Dundee United were entitled to half of this transfer fee. He scored his first goal at [[Ibrox Stadium]] in December in a 3\u20131 defeat.\n\nHe returned home to sign for [[Shelbourne F.C.|Shelbourne]] in 1993 and made his European bow in the [[1993\u201394 European Cup Winners' Cup]] at [[FC Karpaty Lviv]]. Arkins was named on the best league XI for the [[1994\u201395 League of Ireland Premier Division]] season after scoring 13 league goals.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/archive/1995/0421/Pg019.html#Ar01904:5358935558A858E9645AC97961E7EE63C8045BB9645D897968185C69686A |title=Friday, April 21, 1995 \u2013 Page 019 |publisher=The Irish Times |date=21 April 1995 |accessdate=25 December 2012}}</ref> He played in the 1995 [[FAI Cup]] final loss to Derry City.\n\nIn July 1995 Arkins confirmed he had signed a two-year contract at Shelbourne.<ref>{{cite news|title=Article| url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/archive/1995/0721/Pg016.html#Ar01603:3E8AF541CB0F426AF5446B0F449AF5459B0F | work=The Irish Times}}{{Dead link|date=June 2015}}</ref>\n\nHe played in the [[1995\u201396 UEFA Cup]] clashes with [[\u00cd\u00fer\u00f3ttabandalag Akraness]], getting sent off in Iceland.<ref>{{cite news|title=Article |url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/archive/1995/0824/Pg018.html#Ar01806:6A35EA6D360466E6AC69C6C65D55FA6066146A46AC6D56C682F6E28506F3 |work=The Irish Times |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121020175818/http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/archive/1995/0824/Pg018.html |archivedate=20 October 2012 }}</ref>\n\nThe following month he opened the scoring in a friendly against [[Manchester United]] in a game that finished 2\u20132.<ref>{{cite news|title=Article| url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/archive/1995/0812/Pg018.html#Ar01801:1E366E21168821C66E24F6883136A23206B93206A03276BA3276A23456B928C7752B478D2B97732C078D28D8552AF866 | work=The Irish Times}}{{Dead link|date=June 2015}}</ref>\n\nHe signed for Notts County from Shelbourne in September 1995, joining the recently departed Shelbourne manager [[Colin Murphy (footballer born 1950)|Colin Murphy]] at [[Meadow Lane]].<ref>[http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/archive/1995/0908/Pg017.html#Ar01701:0707D516784D0D287D1058970679000739170748FE07A91807A900099917 The Irish Times]</ref>\n\nIn February 1997 he joined [[Portadown F.C.|Portadown]] for \u00a310,000<ref>{{cite news|title=Article| url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/archive/1997/0208/Pg019.html#Ar01907:730A32756A476D89A66F79E16F89A87049E07099A67539E1762A3278BA476E3AA770CABC729AF0752B05754AEF758B04 | work=The Irish Times}}{{Dead link|date=June 2015}}</ref> and scored on his debut at home to Coleraine.\n\nHe made his European bow against [[PFC CSKA Sofia]] in the [[1999\u20132000 UEFA Cup]].<ref>http://www.uefa.com/uefaeuropaleague/season=1999/matches/round=1275/match=56585/postmatch/lineups/index.html</ref>\n\nOn his only appearance representing the Irish League he scored against the [[League of Ireland XI]] at [[Terryland Park]] in November 2000.<ref>{{cite news|title=Article| url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/archive/2000/1102/Pg023.html#Ar02302:72131E75433675431E765336 | work=The Irish Times}}{{Dead link|date=June 2015}}</ref>\n\nHe was a prolific goalscorer, scoring 248 goals in 404 appearances during his nine-year spell with [[Portadown F.C.|Portadown]]. He was an [[Irish Football League|Irish League]] winner with Portadown in 2001/02. Arkins was the top scorer in the Irish League on five occasions.<ref>[http://www.rsssf.com/tablesn/niltops.html Northern Ireland \u2013 List of Topscorers] Rec Sport Soccer Statistics Foundation</ref>\n\nHe remains the only player from the Republic of Ireland to be top scorer in the [[IFA Premiership|Northern Irish Premiership]]. In July 2002 he scored at [[FC Belshina Bobruisk]] in the [[2002\u201303 UEFA Champions League]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Article| url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/soccer/news/2002/07/24/champions_results/.html}} {{Dead link|date=April 2014|bot=RjwilmsiBot}}</ref>\n\nArkins scored in the [[2005-06 UEFA Cup]] against [[Viking FK]].<ref>http://www.uefa.com/uefaeuropaleague/season=2005/matches/round=2206/match=81233/index.html</ref>\n\nHe made 10 appearances in European competition for the Ports.\n\nIn January 2006 he signed for [[Bohemian F.C.|Bohemians]].<ref>http://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/imported/vinny-sails-out-of-ports-28255444.html</ref>\n \nHis last senior goal was scored for Bohs against Bray on 12 May 2006 and his last senior appearance was on 29 August in a losing [[2006 FAI Cup]] tie against his first LOI club [[Shamrock Rovers]] where he sustained a long-term injury that forced him eventually into retirement. He did subsequently sign for [[St Patrick's Athletic]] on a short-term deal but never actually appeared in a competitive game for the Saints due to his growing family.\n\n==International career==\nArkins won representative honours with the [[League of Ireland XI]] and the [[Irish League XI]], as well as eight [[Republic of Ireland national under-21 football team|Republic Ireland U21]], one [[Republic of Ireland B national football team|B]], four schoolboy and three youth caps. Arkins scoring the winner against Turkey in October 1990.<ref>{{cite news|title=Article| url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/archive/1990/1017/Pg017.html#Ar01702:1837801A97951B47801DF7951EC81821682D21A81821C82D3537E737D7FC3558FD380912 | work=The Irish Times}}{{Dead link|date=June 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Honours==\n*'''[[IFA Premiership|Irish League]]'''\n** [[Portadown F.C.|Portadown]] 2001/2002\n*'''[[Irish Cup]]: 2'''\n** [[Portadown F.C.|Portadown]] 1998/99, 2004/05\n*'''[[Mid-Ulster Cup]]: 3'''\n** [[Portadown F.C.|Portadown]] 1997/1998, 2001/2002, 2002/2003\n*'''[[Irish FA Charity Shield]]'''\n** [[Portadown F.C.|Portadown]] 1999/2000\n* '''[[LFA President's Cup]]:'''\n** [[Shelbourne F.C.|Shelbourne]] 1993\n*'''[[PFAI Young Player of the Year]]''':\n** [[Shamrock Rovers]] \u2013 1989/1990\n*'''[[Shamrock Rovers F.C.#Player of the Year Award recipients|SRFC Player of the Year]]:\n** [[Shamrock Rovers]] \u2013 1989/1990\n*'''[[Ulster Footballer of the Year]]'''\n** [[Portadown F.C.|Portadown]] 1999/2000<ref>M. Brodie (ed.), ''Northern Ireland Soccer Yearbook 2009\u20132010'', p. 102; Belfast:Ulster Tatler Publications</ref>\n*'''[[Northern Ireland Football Writers' Association Player of the Year]]:2 '''\n** [[Portadown F.C.|Portadown]] 1999/2000, 2001/2002\n\n{{PFAI Players' Young Player of the Year}}\n\n== Notes ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==References==\n*{{soccerbase|232}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Arkins, Vinny}}\n[[Category:1970 births]]\n[[Category:Shamrock Rovers F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Expatriate association footballers in Northern Ireland]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in England]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Scotland]]\n[[Category:League of Ireland players]]\n[[Category:Association football forwards]]\n[[Category:Irish expatriate sportspeople in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:NIFL Premiership players]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Notts County F.C. players]]\n[[Category:People from Dublin (city)]]\n[[Category:Association footballers from Dublin (city)]]\n[[Category:Portadown F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Republic of Ireland association footballers]]\n[[Category:Republic of Ireland expatriate association footballers]]\n[[Category:Republic of Ireland B international footballers]]\n[[Category:Republic of Ireland under-21 international footballers]]\n[[Category:Republic of Ireland youth international footballers]]\n[[Category:Scottish Football League players]]\n[[Category:Shelbourne F.C. players]]\n[[Category:St Johnstone F.C. players]]\n[[Category:St Patrick's Athletic F.C. players]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n[[Category:Bohemian F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Ulster Footballers of the Year]]\n[[Category:Northern Ireland Football Writers' Association Players of the Year]]\n[[Category:Home Farm F.C. players]]\n[[Category:League of Ireland XI players]]\n[[Category:Republic of Ireland football managers]]\n[[Category:Dundee United F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Stella Maris F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Irish League representative players]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=July 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name               = Vinny Arkins\n| fullname            = Vincent Thomas Arkins<ref>{{Hugman|470|accessdate=25 March 2017}}</ref>\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1970|9|18|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Dublin]], Ireland\n| height              = {{height|m=1.87}}\n| position            = [[Striker (association football)|Striker]] \n| youthyears1 =     \u20131986 | youthclubs1 = [[Stella Maris F.C.|Stella Maris]]\n| youthyears2 = 1986\u20131987 | youthclubs2 = [[Home Farm F.C.|Home Farm]]\n| years1              = 1987\u20131989 |clubs1 = [[Dundee United F.C.|Dundee United]] |caps1 = 0 |goals1 = 0\n| years2              = 1989\u20131991 |clubs2 = [[Shamrock Rovers F.C.|Shamrock Rovers]] |caps2 = 67 |goals2 